<para xml:id="C33.S1.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="16" xml:id="C33.S1.p2.s1">
The main functions treated in this chapter are first the Coulomb radial functions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.p2.m1">F_{\ell}\left(\eta,\rho\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.p2.m2">G_{\ell}\left(\eta,\rho\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.p2.m3">{H^{\pm}_{\ell}}\left(\eta,\rho\right)</Math> (Sommerfeld (1928)), which are used in the case of repulsive Coulomb interactions, and secondly the functions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.p2.m4">f\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.p2.m5">h\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.p2.m6">s\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.p2.m7">c\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)</Math> (Seaton (1982, 2002a)), which are used in the case of attractive Coulomb interactions.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C33.S1.Px1">
<title>Alternative Notations</title>   
<para xml:id="C33.S1.Px1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="17" xml:id="C33.S1.Px1.p1.s1">
 <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.I1.ix1.p1.m1">P_{\ell}(\epsilon,r)=(2\ell+1)!f\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)/2^{\ell+1}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.I1.ix1.p1.m2">Q_{\ell}(\epsilon,r)=-(2\ell+1)!h\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)/(2^{\ell+1}A( \epsilon,\ell))</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="18" xml:id="C33.S1.Px1.p1.s2">
<Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.I1.ix2.p1.m1">f^{(0)}(\epsilon,\ell;r)=f\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.I1.ix2.p1.m2">f(\epsilon,\ell;r)=s\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C33.S1.I1.ix2.p1.m3">g(\epsilon,\ell;r)=c\left(\epsilon,\ell;r\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
